//! @page tool_usage Tool usage guide
//!
//! @brief User-facing map of the command-line tools and their normal flow.
//!
//! The usual entry point is `n65driver`. It accepts source, assembly, object,
//! and archive inputs, dispatches the lower-level tools, and writes the final
//! Intel HEX image unless stopped at an earlier stage.
//!
//! @section tool_usage_pipeline Normal pipeline
//!
//! - `n65cc` compiles `.n` source into assembly.
//! - `n65asm` assembles source into relocatable `.o65` objects or Intel HEX.
//! - `n65ar` bundles `.o65` objects into `.a65` archives for lazy linking.
//! - `n65ld` links objects and archives, lays out memory, resolves relocations,
//!   emits Intel HEX, and optionally writes a map file.
//! - `n65sim` can run an emitted HEX image for smoke and regression checks.
//!
//! @section tool_usage_examples Examples
//!
//! High-level flow:
//!
//! @code{.sh}
//! n65driver -I test test/sieve.n -o sieve.hex
//! n65sim sieve.hex
//! @endcode
//!
//! Direct stage-by-stage flow:
//!
//! @code{.sh}
//! n65cc -quiet -I test test/sieve.n -o sieve.s -dumpbase sieve.n -dumpbase-ext .n -dumpdir ./
//! n65asm -I libraries/nlib/ -o sieve.o65 sieve.s
//! n65ld -o sieve.hex sieve.o65 libraries/nlib/nlib.a65
//! n65sim sieve.hex
//! @endcode
//!
//! @section tool_usage_docs More detailed command references
//!
//! The top-level `README.md` summarizes installation, testing, and the
//! end-to-end workflow. The per-tool README files under `compiler/`,
//! `assembler/`, `linker/`, and `archiver/` describe each command in more
//! detail. Maintainers should start with the module pages linked from the
//! main page and then follow the documented internal functions in the source
//! browser.
